tical guide to the research methods of this important emerging field. William Hoppitt and Kevin Laland define the mechanisms thought to underlie social learning and demonstrate how to distinguish them experimentally in the laboratory. They present techniques for detecting and quantifying social learning in nature, including statistical modeling of the spatial distribution of behavior traits. They also describe the latest theory and empirical findings on social learning strategies, and introduce readers to mathematical methods and models used in the study of cultural evolution. This book is an indispensable tool for researchers and an essential primer for students. Provides a comprehensive, practical guide to social learning research Combines theoretical and empirical approaches Describes techniques for the laboratory and the field Covers social learning mechanisms and strategies, statistical modeling techniques for field data, mathematical modeling of cultural evolution, and more  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLearning in animalsxResearchxMethodology. 0aNATURExAnimalsxGeneral. 0aPsychology, ComparativexResearchxMethodology. 0aSCIENCExLife SciencesxZoologyxGeneral. 0aSocial learningxResearchxMethodology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh  aAristotle.  aacquisition.  aanimal culture.  aanimals.  aasocial learning.  abehavior.  abehavioral repertoires.  abehavioral research.  abehavioral trait.  abiological evolution.  acausal modeling.  achild development.  achildren.  acontrolled diffusion.  acultural evolution.  acultural transmission.  adecision making.  adevelopmental methods.  adiffusion curve analysis.  adiffusion data.  adiffusion experiments.  adiffusion of innovation.  adiffusion.  aecological hypothesis.  aexperimental manipulati